sec.p:
The TDFEM used to determine the vibration response of the plate due to a transient loading F(t) (or a transient incidence wave p0(t)) can be given as follows:
(1){M}{U··}+{C}{U·}+{K}{U}={F(t)}+{T}{p0(t)}
where {M}, {C}, and {K} are the mass, damping, and stiffness matrices of the whole stiffened plate system, respectively; {U}, {U·}, and {U··} are the global nodal displacements, velocity, and acceleration vectors (respectively). {T} is a transformation matrix converting the incidence sound pressure to point forces that act on the nodes of the plate. The damping matrix {C} (Ewins, 2000) is assumed to be proportional to the stiffness matrix {K} and is written as {C}=β{K}, where β=2ηω0, η is the damping factor, and ω0 is the fundamental natural frequency of the plate system.
